<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<DynamicFolderExport>
  <Name>Dynamic Folder Export</Name>
  <Objects>
    <DynamicFolderExportObject>
      <Type>DynamicFolder</Type>
      <Name>Keeper Secrets Manager (Python)</Name>
      <Description>Dynamic credentials from Keeper Secrets Manager (KSM) using Python on Windows and macOS — server, database, login, and SSH key records. Set KSM config path and optional database client paths in Custom Properties.</Description>
      <Notes><![CDATA[<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" />
<title>Keeper Secrets Manager Dynamic Folder</title>
<style type="text/css">
h2 { font-family: Arial; font-size: 16pt; font-weight: bold; }
h3 { font-family: Arial; font-size: 14pt; font-weight: bold; }
p, li { font-family: Arial; font-size: 11pt; }
code { font-family: monospace; background-color: #f0f0f0; padding: 2px 4px; }
</style>

<h2>Keeper Secrets Manager Dynamic Folder</h2>

<p>This Dynamic Folder imports credentials from Keeper Security using the <strong>Keeper Secrets Manager (KSM) SDK</strong>. This Python implementation works on both <strong>Windows and macOS</strong>.</p>

<p>Items are imported as Dynamic Credentials. The username and password fields remain empty after reloading and are only fetched when a connection is established.</p>

<h3>Requirements</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Royal TS v7 or higher / Royal TSX v6 or higher</li>
  <li>Python 3.9 or higher</li>
  <li>Keeper Secrets Manager SDK: <code>pip install keeper-secrets-manager-core</code></li>
  <li>Keeper Business or Enterprise account with Secrets Manager enabled</li>
  <li>KSM Configuration file (.ini, .json, or .base64 from Keeper Vault)</li>
</ul>

<h3>Configuration</h3>
<p>Set the <strong>KSM Config Path</strong> custom property to point to your config file. Supported formats:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>.json</code> - From Keeper Vault → Secrets Manager → Add Device → Configuration File → JSON</li>
  <li><code>.base64</code> - From Keeper Vault → Secrets Manager → Add Device → Configuration File → Base64</li>
  <li><code>.ini</code> - From Keeper CLI: create KSM app, get one-time token, run <code>ksm init default --token YOUR_TOKEN</code></li>
</ul>
<p>All config formats work on both <strong>Windows (Royal TS)</strong> and <strong>macOS (Royal TSX)</strong>. Use the platform-specific path fields (KSM Config Path for Windows / macOS).</p>

<h3>Supported Record Types</h3>
<ul>
  <li><code>login</code> - Standard username/password credentials</li>
  <li><code>serverCredentials</code> - Server credentials with host/port</li>
  <li><code>databaseCredentials</code> - Database credentials (MySQL, PostgreSQL, MSSQL, Oracle, MongoDB, Redis; Windows: External Application; macOS: Terminal/iTerm2 with helper script)</li>
  <li><code>sshKeys</code> - SSH private keys (KeyFileContent supported)</li>
</ul>
<p>For <code>databaseCredentials</code>: Supports <strong>MySQL</strong>, <strong>PostgreSQL</strong>, <strong>MSSQL</strong>, <strong>Oracle</strong>, <strong>MongoDB</strong>, and <strong>Redis</strong>. Database type is read from the Keeper record's Type field. <strong>Windows</strong> uses External Application; <strong>macOS</strong> uses Terminal (iTerm2-compatible) with a helper script. Set each database client path you use and KSM Config Path in Custom Properties. On macOS, the helper script is written to <code>~/.config/royal-keeper/db_connect.py</code> (launcher and helper use safe quoting and atomic writes; database passwords are passed via environment variables or short-lived local files where the client supports it). Credentials are not written to the Royal document or script logs.</p>

<h3>Security notes</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Windows External Application</strong> builds command lines using Royal credential tokens (<code>$$EffectivePassword$$</code>, etc.). After Royal substitutes values, secrets may be visible in process listings like any other launched app—this is a limitation of the External Application model, not unique to this folder.</li>
  <li><strong>macOS</strong> launcher scripts quote all paths and arguments (<code>shlex</code>) to avoid shell injection from malicious paths in Custom Properties.</li>
  <li><strong>.base64</strong> KSM configs are decoded to a restrictive (0600) temp file during each script run and removed when the run finishes.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Usage</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Reload the Dynamic Folder to see your Keeper credentials</li>
  <li>Create a new connection (SSH, RDP, SFTP, etc.)</li>
  <li>Enter the host and port manually</li>
  <li>In the Credentials tab, select "Specify a credential name"</li>
  <li>Choose your Keeper credential from the dropdown</li>
  <li>Connect - credentials are fetched securely from Keeper</li>
</ol>

<h3>Documentation</h3>
<p><strong>Keeper:</strong> Create a Secrets Manager application, share records, and obtain a configuration file — see the <a href="https://docs.keeper.io/en/keeperpam/secrets-manager/quick-start-guide">Secrets Manager Quick Start</a> and <a href="https://docs.keeper.io/en/keeperpam/secrets-manager">Secrets Manager documentation</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Royal TS / Royal TSX:</strong> Importing Dynamic Folders, plugins, and connection types — see <a href="https://www.royalapplications.com/ts/win">Royal TS</a> and <a href="https://www.royalapplications.com/ts/mac">Royal TSX</a> product help.</p>

<h3>Author</h3>
<p>Keeper Security</p>
]]></Notes>
